			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Undubbed wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Ok, I can load a rom that doesn't have a mapper, no problem. However, I'm trying to get Metroid loaded, but it apparently doesn't have chrom and has 8 prgrom banks. </div><br /><br />If a iNES ROM does not have CHR-ROM, that means the cart uses a RAM chip where the ROM chip would be.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Undubbed wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Looking at the rom file in hex editor and comparing the pattern table values displayed in FCEUX's Hex Editor, it seems that the graphics reside at prgrom bank 6(at 0x18010 in the rom file). Ok, that's great for Metroid, but I don't know what the general method is for extracting the graphics and loading them into the pattern table for any rom with no chrom.<br /><br />I think it's just my ignorance in exactly what happens when the nes boots. I was under the impression that when the NES boots, it automatically loads the ppu's pattern tables with the chrom(worked for me so far...). But if there is no chrom present...then what? I've yet to see in the mm1 mapper docs, how the pattern tables are loaded, so I'm pretty confused here.</div>
<br />
<br />The NES doesn't load anything on its own. Many different PPU accesses go out to the cart while rendering a frame. When the PPU reads pattern tables, it is just reading whatever it is given from whichever chip on the cart happens to respond to the read (or write for that matter). There is no memory for pattern tables in the NES console. 
<br />
<br />When a game uses a RAM chip for graphics, it will have to write to the pattern tables to fill it with data. 
<br />
<br />I hope what I have written helps (and is at least accurate on a basic level).
<br />
<br />EDIT: I should probably mention that this applies as well to PRG-ROM. One of the most common mistakes is to use memcpy or a loop to copy data from the ROM to "PRG-ROM" arrays when you should just keep track of pointers for each bank (the smallest banks used in commercial game mappers is 4KB/1KB PRG/CHR, IIRC).</div>

