					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Undubbed wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So the memory in the cart is part of the system, huh?</div><br />As long as there isn't any dust on the connectors, this is true.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I always thought that the memory in the cart was completely copied into the nes's memory and if the program needed to switch it would grab the code from the cart, so that's what I did with my emulator(this time, grabbing code from the rom file).</div><br />Sounds like Famicom Disk System.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Perhaps I was thinking along the lines of cd-based game where the game doesn't immediately screw up cause you took the CD out cause everything that the game currently needs is in ram.</div>
<br />Some systems allow for a completely RAM-based program. There have to be 1. no continuous communication between the CIC, 2. enough video memory to make a picture, and 3. interrupt vectors pointed at RAM or the system's BIOS. Systems meeting this are disc-based consoles as well as the Game Boy Advance and Nintendo DS. You can even load up one town on Animal Crossing in your GameCube, take the disc out, put it in your Wii, and load up another town.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

