					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Undubbed wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">So the memory in the cart is part of the system, huh?</div><br />Yup. The CPU is directly connected to the PRG chip and the PPU to the CHR chip, and both chips are continuously accessed as the program runs.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I always thought that the memory in the cart was completely copied into the nes's memory</div><br />Maybe you thought that because the concept of bankswitching is hard to understand at first. For most people it's easier to see bankswitching as memory transfers, but that's not the case at all.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'll have to redesign my memory then.</div><br />Yeah, you'll probably want to break your PRG and CHR memory into smaller units (8KB for PRG and 1KB for CHR should cover most mappers - NSF needs 4KB PRG bankswitching though) and use pointers or arrays to access the correct blocks.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Perhaps I was thinking along the lines of cd-based game where the game doesn't immediately screw up cause you took the CD out cause everything that the game currently needs is in ram.</div>
<br />Well, the Famicom Disk System uses floppies for the games, and I'm pretty sure that the programs/graphics are copied from the floppy to RAM. You still can't unplug the thing though, because it has a mapper and the RAM that holds the program and graphics.</div>

